Part I: Scope and Introduction

The aim of this project is to build classification and clustering models based on the US Accident data set. This data set gives us information about 2000 observations/accidents that occurred over the years 2000-2015, including key variables like details of the accident, machinery used, experience of the individual and degree of the injury.

In the classification models, we use supervised learning models like Logistic regression and the Naive Bayes classifier on the training data to train our models, and then use the calibration and test sets to see how well our models perform. Our question in mind is to predict whether an accident is serious based on our other independent variables. We then do a comparison on which method produces more accurate results.

In unsupervised learning, clustering techniques like k-Means are used on numerical variables in the model to draw clusters, which groups similar observations with each other.

Single Variable Models with Categorical Variables:

Before we continue with our analysis, we first want to convert our categorical columns to a prediction columns with the proportion of observations that resulted in a serious injury. Due to the fact that some of the categorical columns have many levels/factors, this is an essential step to numericalize these variables so we can interpret them better, as also for our model to deal with numerical values than multilevel variables.

mkPredC = function(outCol, varCol, appCol) {
  pPos <- sum(outCol == pos) / length(outCol)
  naTab <- table(as.factor(outCol[is.na(varCol)]))
  pPosWna <- (naTab/sum(naTab))[pos]
  vTab <- table(as.factor(outCol), varCol)
  pPosWv <- (vTab[pos, ] + 1.0e-3*pPos) / (colSums(vTab) + 1.0e-3)
  pred <- pPosWv[appCol]
  pred[is.na(appCol)] <- pPosWna
  pred[is.na(pred)] <- pPos
  pred
}

for(v in catVars) {
pi <- paste('pred', v, sep='')
accidentTrain[,pi] = mkPredC(accidentTrain[,outcome], accidentTrain[,v], accidentTrain[,v])
accidentCal[,pi] = mkPredC(accidentTrain[,outcome], accidentTrain[,v], accidentCal[,v])
testSet[,pi] = mkPredC(accidentTrain[,outcome], accidentTrain[,v], testSet[,v])
}

Single Variable Perfomances AUC and Deviance Reduction from the null model To measure single variable model performance, we use AUC and deviance reduction, based on log likelihood to assess the quality of the classifier. A brief introduction and explaination of these 2 measures are given below:

AUC The AUC is built upon the receiver operating curve (ROC), that shows us the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds, based on the two parameters: True Positive Rate (TPR) and False Positive Rate (FPR). (Google ML). AUC or Area Under the (ROC) Curve gives us an aggregate measure of performance across all possible classification thresholds. The bigger the AUC, the better the model is.

Deviance Reduction Deviance is defined by a difference in the log likelihoods, comparing the null model with the given model.

As we want to find the best single variable model based off the null model, we want to select the single variable model that gives us the largest deviance reduction to the null/saturated model.

Helper Function for AUC

calcAUC <- function(predcol,outcol) {
perf <- performance(prediction(predcol,outcol==pos),'auc')
as.numeric(perf@y.values)
}

We then select the best categorical variables for further analysis, based on AUC. We can then apply a cutoff on the training AUC, and then look at the calibration AUC to assess the performance.

AUC (Train and Calibration) Performance on Categorical Variables

bestCatVars = c()

100 Fold Cross-Validation

for (var in bestCatVars) {
  auc = rep(0, 100)
  for (j in 1:length(auc)) {
    useForCalRep = rbinom(n=nrow(trainingSet), size=1, prob=0.2) > 0
    predRep = mkPredC(trainingSet[!useForCalRep,outcome],
                      trainingSet[!useForCalRep,var],
                      trainingSet[useForCalRep,var])
    auc[j] = calcAUC(predRep, trainingSet[useForCalRep,outcome])
  }
print(sprintf("%s: mean: %4.3f; sd: %4.3f", var, mean(auc), sd(auc)))
}

The Double Density Plot The double density plots gives us a visual understanding and representation of the predicted probabilities on the outcome variable.

Helper Functions and Plotting the DD plots using ggplot

get_legend<-function(myggplot){
    tmp <- ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(myggplot))
    leg <- which(sapply(tmp$grobs, function(x) x$name) == "guide-box")
    legend <- tmp$grobs[[leg]]
    return(legend)
    }

mkPredN = function(outCol, varCol, appCol) {
# compute the cuts
cuts <- unique(
quantile(varCol, probs=seq(0, 1, 0.1), na.rm=T)) # discretize the numerical columns
varC <- cut(varCol,cuts) 
appC <- cut(appCol,cuts) 
mkPredC(outCol,varC,appC) 
}

Feature Selection using log Likelihood:

logLikelihood <- function(ytrue, ypred, epsilon=1e-6, pos=1) {
  sum(ifelse(ytrue==pos, log(ypred+epsilon), log(1-ypred+epsilon)), na.rm=T)
}

Performance Measures: Accuracy, Precision, Recall and F1 Score Performance Measures are used to assess the goodness of fit or accuracy of a model. We shall briefly discuss the different measures below:

Accuracy: Provides the percentage of correctly predicted values Precision: True Positives over all predicted positive results Recall: True Positive over all actual positive results F1: Harmonic mean of precision and recall.

The log likelihood function to calculate F1 score.

logLikelihood2 <- function(ytrue, ypred, epsilon=1e-6, pos=1) {
  sum(ifelse(ytrue==pos, log(ypred+epsilon), log(1-ypred+epsilon)), na.rm=T)
}

Testing whether my function works

ypred.calibration = as.numeric(as.character(predict(model.log, newdata = accidentCal)))
ytrue.calibration = accidentCal[,outcome]

Performance Measures Function:

performanceMeasures = function(ytrue, ypred, model.name = "model", threshold = 0.5)  {
  # normalised deviance
  dev.norm = -2 * logLikelihood(ytrue, ypred)/length(ypred)
  #confusion matrix:
  confMat = table(ytrue, ypred >= threshold)
  accuracy = sum(diag(confMat)) / sum(confMat)
  precision = confMat[2, 2] / sum(confMat[, 2])
  recall = confMat[2, 2] / sum(confMat[2, ])
  f1 = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)
  data.frame(model = model.name, accuracy = accuracy, precision = precision, recall = recall, f1 = f1, dev.norm = dev.norm)
}

panderOpt = function(){

pp_table = function(model, xtrain, ytrain, xtest, ytest, xcal, ycal, threshold =0.5){
  panderOpt()
  perf_justify = 'lrrrrr'
  
  pred_train = as.numeric(as.character(predict(model.log, newdata = accidentTrain)))
  pred_test = as.numeric(as.character(predict(model.log, newdata = testSet)))
  pred_cal =  as.numeric(as.character(predict(model.log, newdata = accidentCal)))
  
  train_df = performanceMeasures(ytrain,pred_train, model.name = 'training')
  cal_df = performanceMeasures(ycal,pred_cal, model.name = 'calibration')
  test_df = performanceMeasures(ytest,pred_test, model.name = 'test')
  
  perftable <- rbind(train_df, cal_df, test_df)
  pandoc.table(perftable, justify = perf_justify)
}

plot_ROC = function(predcoltrain, outcoltrain, predcolcal, outcolcal, predcoltest, outcoltest) {
  roc_train = rocit(score=predcoltrain, class=outcoltrain==pos)
  roc_cal = rocit(score=predcolcal, class=outcolcal==pos)
  roc_test = rocit(score=predcoltest, class=outcoltest==pos)
  
  plot(roc_train, col=c('blue','green'), lwd=3,legend=FALSE,YIndex=FALSE,values=TRUE,asp=1)
  lines(roc_cal$TPR ~ roc_cal$FPR, lwd=3, col=c('red','green'), asp=1)
  lines(roc_test$TPR ~ roc_test$FPR, lwd=3, col=c('orange','green'), asp=1)
  legend("bottomright",col=c("blue",'red','orange'), c("Training","Calibration","Test"),lwd=2)
}

Part VI: Clustering

Clustering Models: In clustering, we use our numerical variables for unsupervised learning. Here, we focus on k-Means Clustering, which finds assigns each observation to each cluster center based on some distance parameter, in which we use the euclidean distance, which then repeats and reassigns the points until convergence, where all the points are assigned and stop moving.

Variable Selection and Scaling the data

scale.accident = scale(accident)

Before we perform k-means, we require the data to be void of any NA variables, therefore, we use na.omit to clean the data. Disclaimer: When we remove the observations with NA, we are taking out almost half the data set. Here we might lose infomation, but having 1000 observations is still a good number to work with.

Finding the optimal number of clusters (kmeansruns) To find the optimal number of clusters, we can use the library kmeansruns, which cross validates the kmeans criterion of either CH or ASW on each number of clusters, in this case we will limit from a minimum of 1 cluster to a maximum of 10 clusters.

The CH index is used as a measure of cluster goodness, where it is the ratio of the between cluster variance (B) and within cluster variance (W). Our aim is to maximise the the CH

The ASW or Average Silhouette Width is also used for assessment to find the optimal number of clusters, which we also want to maximise.

k.ch = kmeansruns(scale.clean, krange=1:10, criterion='ch')
k.asw = kmeansruns(scale.clean, krange=1:10, criterion='asw')

kmcrit = data.frame(k=1:10, ch=k.ch$crit, asw=k.asw$crit)

ggkmeans2 = ggplot(kmcrit, aes(x=k, y=asw)) + geom_point() + geom_line(color='blue') + labs(y='ASW') + scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:10, labels=1:10)

We can see that using the 2 heuristic values, perhaps the better option is to choose 4 clusters. This is because the ASW is at its highest at 4 clusters. However, for CH the best choice is show to be 2, but there is also a second mode at 4, where after more than 4 clusters, the CH starts to drop off, so there is evidence that 4 clusters might be the optimal choice over 2.

Convex Hull Function and plotting the clusters. 

find_CHull = function(proj2Ddf,groups){
  do.call(rbind, lapply(unique(groups), FUN=function(c){
    f<-subset(proj2Ddf,cluster==c)
    f[chull(f),]
  }
  )) 
}

k.meanshull = find_CHull(kmeans2D, km4$cluster)

ggplot(kmeans2D, aes(x=PC1, y=PC2)) + geom_point(aes(shape=cluster,color=cluster))+ geom_polygon(data=k.meanshull,aes(group=cluster,fill=as.factor(cluster)), alpha=0.4,linetype=0)+theme(text=element_text(size=10))

Finally, we plot our clusters on the PC1 and PC2 axes. We can see that the k-means clustering does a decent job at separating the clusters.
